<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-560-333  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 560 333.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 29 1990 v24 n43 p76(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>City cops take byte out of crime. (Dallas police and mobile dataterminals)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilder, Clinton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Officers on the Dallas Police force use mobile data terminals tohelp them identify wanted vehicles.andP;  The anti-crime tool is anintegral part of the technological police infrastructure and hasbecome as important as 12-gauge shotguns in fighting crime.andP;  The$10.2 million system includes computerized fingerprint matching,automatic location of 911 calls and an 800 MHz cellular telephoneinstalled in every patrol car.andP;  Police using mobile terminalsquery the information system twice as much as they did when verbalrequests were required and can get important information quicklywhen they stop a car, including whether the driver might be armedor dangerous.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Law enforcementData Terminal EquipmentMunicipal GovernmentPortable computersCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>